    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Violence in the Park: How Did It Happen?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lisa Tolin letter on assaults against women in Central Park in hours after Puerto Rican Day parade; calls for passage of Repr Carolyn Maloney's bill to require US attorney general to count gender-motivated bias crimes (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Park Victims Say the Police Did Not Help'' (news article, June 13):</p>
        <p>The assaults in Central Park were apparently aimed at women and have terrified women around the city and beyond. It is time to start recognizing women as a class of people who are routinely attacked with impunity. If we cannot do this in our hearts, we should do so in our laws.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Park Victims Say the Police Did Not Help'' (news article, June 13):</p>
        <p>The assaults in Central Park were apparently aimed at women and have terrified women around the city and beyond. It is time to start recognizing women as a class of people who are routinely attacked with impunity. If we cannot do this in our hearts, we should do so in our laws.</p>
        <p>Congress should act to pass Representative Carolyn B. Maloney's Hate Crime Statistics Improvement Act, which would require the attorney general to count gender-motivated bias crimes. The full extent of the problem will be realized only when these crimes are counted.</p>
        <p>LISA TOLIN  Brooklyn, June 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
